##############################################

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "contextFraction.pl",
  "PCCmacros.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);

##############################################

Context("LimitedFraction");
Context()->flags->set(showMixedNumbers=>0);
Context()->flags->set(allowMixedNumbers=>1);
Context()->flags->set(requirePureFractions=>1);

do {
   $num1 = random(1,5,1);
   do {$den1 = random(6,10,1);} until (gcd($num1,$den1)==1);
   $frac1 = Fraction($num1,$den1);

   $num2 = random(1,5,1);
   do {$den2 = random(6,10,1);} until (gcd($num2,$den2)==1);
   $frac2 = Fraction($num2,$den2);

   $ans = ($frac1 * $frac2)->reduce;
   @temp = $ans->value;
   $numAns = $temp[0];
   $denAns = $temp[1];
} until ((gcd($num1,$den2)==1)&&(gcd($num2,$den1)==1));

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

Multiply: [`` \frac{[$num1]}{[$den1]} \cdot \frac{[$num2]}{[$den2]} ``]

[@KeyboardInstructions("If needed, use an improper fraction in your answer. Don't use a mixed number.")@]**

    [_______]{$ans}

END_PGML

##############################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

To multiply two fractions, simply multiply both numerators and both denominators. We have:

    [`` 
\begin{aligned}[t]
   \frac{[$num1]}{[$den1]} \cdot \frac{[$num2]}{[$den2]}
           &= \frac{[$num1] \cdot [$num2]}{[$den1] \cdot [$den2]} \\
           &= \frac{[$numAns]}{[$denAns]}
\end{aligned}
    ``]

The answer to this question is [``\frac{[$numAns]}{[$denAns]}``].

END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();



